CNN Cancer Detection¶

github: https://github.com/JulianZhan/cnn_cancer_detection kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/c/histopathologic-cancer-detection/overview

Introduction¶

This notebook implements Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) models to identify metastatic cancer from small image patches, I aso use different models architect to find the best model for the task. The data comes from Kaggle.

Data Description¶

Here we load the dataset, which includes labels indicating the presence of metastatic tissue in image patches and the image content. And labels are binary, with 1 indicating the presence of metastatic tissue and 0 indicating no cancer.

Image Visualization¶

Visualizing sample images from the dataset gives insight into the data quality and variance. Here, we can find the no cancer images are usually cleaner and contain more white space, less texture. In contrast, images with cancer present have more texture, more dots, and less white space.

In [5]:
def display_images(images, labels, num=10):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    for i in range(num):
        ax = plt.subplot(2, num // 2, i + 1)
        img = mpimg.imread(os.path.join(data_dir, 'train', images.iloc[i]))
        ax.imshow(img)
        ax.set_title('Label: ' + str(labels.iloc[i]))
        ax.axis('off')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()


# Visualize sample images with their labels
sample_images = labels.sample(n=10, random_state=0).reset_index(drop=True)
display_images(sample_images['id'], sample_images['label'])

Data Preprocessing¶

Before training, we need to preprocess our data. This includes splitting the data into training and validation sets, normalizing image pixel values, and augmenting the data to improve model generalization.

In [6]:
# Data preprocessing
labels['label'] = labels['label'].astype(str)
train_df, val_df = train_test_split(labels, test_size=0.2, random_state=0, stratify=labels['label'])
datagen = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1. / 255, horizontal_flip=True, vertical_flip=True)

train_gen = datagen.flow_from_dataframe(
    dataframe=train_df,
    directory=os.path.join(data_dir, 'train'),
    x_col='id',
    y_col='label',
    target_size=(16, 16),
    class_mode='binary',
    batch_size=128
)

val_gen = datagen.flow_from_dataframe(
    dataframe=val_df,
    directory=os.path.join(data_dir, 'train'),
    x_col='id',
    y_col='label',
    target_size=(16, 16),
    class_mode='binary',
    batch_size=128
)

Model Building¶

We define two CNN architectures here. One is a base shallow model with broader layers, and the other is a deeper but narrower model. The two models with different design philosophy will help us compare the performance of different architectures.

In [7]:
def build_base_model(input_shape=(16, 16, 3)):
    model = Sequential([
        Conv2D(4, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=input_shape),
        MaxPooling2D(3, 3),
        Conv2D(8, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
        MaxPooling2D(3, 3),
        Flatten(),
        Dense(4, activation='relu'),
        Dropout(0.3),
        Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
    ])
    return model
In [8]:
def build_deep_model(input_shape=(16, 16, 3)):
    model = Sequential([
        Conv2D(4, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same', input_shape=input_shape),
        Conv2D(4, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
        MaxPooling2D(2, 2),
        Conv2D(4, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
        Conv2D(4, (3, 3), activation='relu', padding='same'),
        MaxPooling2D(2, 2),
        Flatten(),
        Dense(2, activation='relu'),
        Dropout(0.3),
        Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')
    ])
    return model

Model Experimentation¶

Here I try running experiments with different hyperparameters to fine-tune the models. This experiment with various combinations of optimizers and learning rates help to find the most effective settings for our models.

In [9]:
def plot_metrics(history):
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'], label='Training Accuracy')
    plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'], label='Validation Accuracy')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy')
    plt.legend()

    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(history.history['loss'], label='Training Loss')
    plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'], label='Validation Loss')
    plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')
    plt.legend()

    plt.show()
In [10]:
def experiment(model_fn, optimizer, learning_rate, epochs=3):
    model = model_fn()
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer(learning_rate=learning_rate),
                  loss='binary_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    history = model.fit(train_gen, epochs=epochs, validation_data=val_gen, verbose=1)
    best_val_accuracy = max(history.history['val_accuracy'])
    plot_metrics(history)
    return model, history, best_val_accuracy
In [11]:
optimizers = [Adam, SGD]
learning_rates = [0.003]
batch_size = 512
train_gen.batch_size = batch_size
val_gen.batch_size = batch_size
best_base_model = None
best_deep_model = None
best_base_accuracy = 0
best_deep_accuracy = 0
best_base_settings = {}
best_deep_settings = {}

for model_fn, model_name in [(build_base_model, "Base Model"), (build_deep_model, "Deep Model")]:
    for optimizer in optimizers:
        for lr in learning_rates:
            print(f"\nTesting {model_name} with {optimizer.__name__} and learning rate: {lr}")
            model, history, val_accuracy = experiment(model_fn, optimizer, lr)
            if model_name == "Base Model" and val_accuracy > best_base_accuracy:
                best_base_accuracy = val_accuracy
                best_base_model = model
                best_base_settings = {'optimizer': optimizer.__name__, 'learning_rate': lr, 'model': model_name}
            elif model_name == "Deep Model" and val_accuracy > best_deep_accuracy:
                best_deep_accuracy = val_accuracy
                best_deep_model = model
                best_deep_settings = {'optimizer': optimizer.__name__, 'learning_rate': lr, 'model': model_name}

print(f"Best Base Model Settings: {best_base_settings} with accuracy: {best_base_accuracy}")
print(f"Best Deep Model Settings: {best_deep_settings} with accuracy: {best_deep_accuracy}")

Model Evaluation¶

To further evaluate model performance, we generate confusion matrices and ROC curves. These metrics help us understand how well the model is performing in terms of true positive rate, false positive rate, and overall accuracy.

In [13]:
def evaluate_and_compare_models(base_model, deep_model, data_generator):
    for model, label in [(base_model, "Base Model"), (deep_model, "Deep Model")]:
        evaluate_model(model, data_generator, label)


def evaluate_model(model, data_generator, label):
    predictions = model.predict(data_generator)
    y_pred = [1 if x > 0.5 else 0 for x in predictions]
    y_true = data_generator.classes

    # Confusion Matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt="d", linewidths=.5, square=True, cmap='Blues')
    plt.ylabel('Actual label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    plt.title(f'Confusion Matrix - {label}', size=15)
    plt.show()

    # ROC Curve
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_true, predictions)
    roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange', lw=2, label=f'ROC curve (area = {roc_auc:.2f})')
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=2, linestyle='--')
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title(f'Receiver Operating Characteristic - {label}')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()


# Evaluate and compare both best models
evaluate_and_compare_models(best_base_model, best_deep_model, val_gen)

Model Prediction¶

The best model from the experiments is deep model with Adam optimizer and learning rate 0.003. We load the best model and make predictions on the test set. The predictions are then saved to a CSV file for submission to Kaggle.

Conclusion¶

In this notebook, we implemented CNN models to detect metastatic cancer from small image patches. We experimented with different model architectures and hyperparameters to find the best model for the task. The deep model with Adam optimizer and learning rate 0.003 performed the best, achieving an accuracy of 0.96 on the validation set. The model was then used to make predictions on the test set, and the results were saved to a CSV file for submission to Kaggle.
